<TITLE> ACC to explain notices to Khaleda </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 24 (bdnews24.com)  The High Court on Monday asked the corruption watchdog to explain why their notices to the BNP chief would not be declared illegal. The court gave the order to the Anti-corruption Commission regarding its notices to Khaleda Zia in the Ziaur Rahman Charitable Trust and Bhairab Bridge graft cases. Bench of justices Md Ashraful Islam and SM Emdadul Haque gave the order based on two petitions by the BNP chief. Anti-corruption Commission chairman, secretary, commissioner and investigators concerned were asked to respond within a week. ACC issued eight notices to Khaleda between Feb 15 and May 2 asking for her statements regarding irregularities in Bhairab Bridge and illegal bank transactions in the Ziaur Rahman Charitable Trust. The opposition leader made two separate writ petitions regarding the legality of the notices on May 18. Barrister Moudud Ahmed argued for the defendant while advocate Anisul Haque stood for the commission. Attorney general Mahbubey Alam spoke for the state. b
